                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Herbalife vs. Activist: Just Maybe He&#8217;s Right</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Amie Tsang                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2016-08-02T10:46:33+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 2, 2016 6:46 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 2, 2016 6:46 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/02/morning-agenda-herbalife-vs-activist-just-maybe-hes-right/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Herbalife vs. Activist: Just Maybe He&#8217;s Right" data-description="Uber Waves the White Flag | Big Banks Push Instant Payments">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>HERBALIFE VS. ACTIVIST: JUST MAYBE HE&#8217;S RIGHT</strong> Bill Ackman, the activist investor, has been painted as a loser in his quest to shut down Herbalife, the nutritional supplement company, but a Federal Trade Commission&#8217;s complaint has vindicated his claims, <a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?location=4z5Q7LhI+KVBjmEgFdYACPLKh239P3pgf8jIzNgNYUkX6jrpfwo+Eh/ZqTf6HH1ecAIGTzNe4tNkUEyl+Fg+dKeWbfDJgVonuJyDL/YN6jBwah9S19HfonyFm/dpQeota+tFHQFLI0V5k5HHcldFkkBOLVOlY2V0dUVaiFKAOTn/k5bLSFv0uih+6YpVRsJccSiFpDIFxHpSfR0XrcYh4w==&amp;campaign_id=97&amp;instance_id=79976&amp;segment_id=93081&amp;user_id=a17d64ad249adfd588c6df81d8c6c5b4&amp;regi_id=72489293">Andrew Ross Sorkin</a> writes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Herbalife was responsible for &#8220;deceiving hundreds of thousands of hopeful people,&#8221; said Edith Ramirez, who oversees the F.T.C. &#8220;The small minority of Herbalife distributors who did make a lot of money were paid by Herbalife not for selling the company&#8217;s products, but for buying the products themselves and then successfully recruiting large networks of others to do the same.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There have been questions about Mr. Ackman&#8217;s tactics, lobbying regulators and members of Congress, as well as moral questions about &#8220;shorting,&#8221; or betting against a company&#8217;s stock, but this does seem to be an example where an investor acted as a check on the market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>UBER WAVES THE WHITE FLAG IN CHINA</strong> Uber has become yet another company that has failed to capitalize on its foothold in China, but it avoided making many of the same mistakes as its American tech forebears along the way. It created local teams that were able to respond quickly, and the co-founder and chief executive, Travis Kalanick, put in time meeting with Chinese officials. But Didi made it clear it was in the fight for the long run and <a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?location=4z5Q7LhI+KVBjmEgFdYACPLKh239P3pgf8jIzNgNYUkX6jrpfwo+Eh/ZqTf6HH1eDGduyRgML0ozH23GNgBpCmhubnJevUBm4JKQj3Icb8qOBu5AOB7iFEIFMcRkOM4GTPjqKGfqkQpX55LuMjOx9OoZBPz188UKU9SV0G7D2LTLFw3r5Z+ZCg==&amp;campaign_id=97&amp;instance_id=79976&amp;segment_id=93081&amp;user_id=a17d64ad249adfd588c6df81d8c6c5b4&amp;regi_id=72489293">Uber&#8217;s investors</a> wanted an end to the battle.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They may be reassured, but customers and drivers in China could be hurt as commissions drop. Uber may well want to focus on building national monopolies elsewhere now, but its stake in Didi now makes it an indirect part owner of its competitor Lyft, which has also been a useful ally in battles with regulators and taxi drivers. This all seems to point to a less directly competitive future, <a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?location=4z5Q7LhI+KWdRQP9hbGa63VB0atKD7D51vazWrOTUFNi5yTGFMbwIvemEQ/OLHac9PHjImjUPtISxaQ2Fx8tHR190DgWlRt6mG3+LeAgPX0JdnjdXCdThV2TzBKW12HGQfwmDRL1ZHVM2eKdg5Iwtw61h3EbujqYW8B1yYb1I7nNpDcAfQx39mIATEYVfQ6A&amp;campaign_id=97&amp;instance_id=79976&amp;segment_id=93081&amp;user_id=a17d64ad249adfd588c6df81d8c6c5b4&amp;regi_id=72489293">Justin Fox</a> writes on Bloomberg View.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some view having two poles of leadership as beneficial with the giants of China and the United States competing for customers in emerging markets like India, the Middle East and Africa. But others foresee a series of deals in which those titans carve out their<a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?location=4z5Q7LhI+KVBjmEgFdYACPLKh239P3pgf8jIzNgNYUk0vPnuj1Q7VY3/erXLQHRu00Dtb7ZSCRcqKNtp7zgc+v5SSSdLlQFsTPjqKGfqkQpX55LuMjOx9OoZBPz188UKU9SV0G7D2LTLFw3r5Z+ZCg==&amp;campaign_id=97&amp;instance_id=79976&amp;segment_id=93081&amp;user_id=a17d64ad249adfd588c6df81d8c6c5b4&amp;regi_id=72489293"> spheres of influence.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> The Securities and Exchange Commission Equity Market Structure Advisory Committee meets at 9:30 a.m. Data on income and spending for June will be published at 8:30 a.m. Pfizer and Procter &amp; Gamble report their second-quarter earnings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>BIG BANKS PUSH INSTANT PAYMENTS</strong> The snail&#8217;s pace at which money is processed has led many Americans to use mobile payments services like Paypal&#8217;s Venmo or Square Cash. Offerings like Apple Pay and pressure from the Federal Reserve&#8217;s &#8220;faster payments committee&#8221; have also heightened competition to control the payment network of the future. And banks are catching up &#8211; allowing their customers to send money to accounts in seconds &#8211; in the hope of vying with these companies, as well as Visa and MasterCard, in the market for instant payments.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If they do not respond, <a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?location=4z5Q7LhI+KVBjmEgFdYACPLKh239P3pgf8jIzNgNYUkX6jrpfwo+Eh/ZqTf6HH1eVVyi0S/+WwoGWkn/qPB1SjA9Slp/aW7Irf5Uk7gwTRd6ASPstYhdTIYJUlCZjXP8LREzHcDJ7fOvKOj31aeLWoV/IvawS68zTTHbnzR3ohoSBL+k2EtEs/MSDJS9qGw3&amp;campaign_id=97&amp;instance_id=79976&amp;segment_id=93081&amp;user_id=a17d64ad249adfd588c6df81d8c6c5b4&amp;regi_id=72489293">banks could be relegated</a> to performing less profitable back-office functions for newer payment companies and they would lose their first point of contact with a consumer, which allows them to sell other products, like loans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Contact <a href="mailto:amie.tsang@nytimes.com">amie.tsang@nytimes.com</a></em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why Corporate America Is Leaving the Suburbs for the City</strong> Companies including McDonald&#8217;s and General Electric are moving headquarters to cities like Boston and Chicago, partly as a lure to younger employees.<br />
<a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?location=4z5Q7LhI+KVBjmEgFdYACPLKh239P3pgf8jIzNgNYUkX6jrpfwo+Et9icYmY6J0IqVGm9RxtCGnGuqp5YLwnY5GHKcJYugYbi5/onEXTUhmLSel38GHibUXAzb7ZUuUzHh/vyu2CjAJj6U/zjTQ//vvaRB8r9w7BDrWHcRu6OphbwHXJhvUjuc2kNwB9DHf2YgBMRhV9DoA=&amp;campaign_id=97&amp;instance_id=79976&amp;segment_id=93081&amp;user_id=a17d64ad249adfd588c6df81d8c6c5b4&amp;regi_id=72489293">NYT Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Warren Buffett Is Latest Billionaire to Excoriate Donald Trump</strong> Mr. Buffett, in Omaha with Hillary Clinton, unleashed a withering attack on Mr. Trump for refusing to release his tax returns and for misleading voters about his success as a businessman.<br />
<a href="//p.nytimes.com/email/re?location=4z5Q7LhI+KVBjmEgFdYACPLKh239P3pgf8jIzNgNYUnGU/3bNb5Zd4Uc5TVV+KVye0ahT6fGO/hh4S/imGFUld/WvBJVOxeULZIgUBRDZh6rtA98TH7TJkZXKmiQ5jYGjlyT4gTC11UYLlBu0wjvaA==&amp;campaign_id=97&amp;instance_id=79976&amp;segment_id=93081&amp;user_id=a17d64ad249adfd588c6df81d8c6c5b4&amp;regi_id=72489293">NYT Â»</a></p>
